        "content": "<p>That's fantastic, thank you all! Your lean skills are through the roof :)</p>\n<p>In the example that Ruben gave, how did you know that <code>simp[S]</code> is going to turn <code>a ∈ S n</code> into  <code>n ≤ a ∧ a ≤ n + 1</code>. Is it something worth memorising, or is the rule of thumb to usually try <code>simp[X]</code>, whenever <code>X</code> is some complex object that needs breaking down into simpler definitions?</p>",
        "id": 474090324,
        "sender_full_name": "Adam Kurkiewicz",
        "timestamp": 1727803882
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Well, you just defined <code>S</code>, so the only thing you can do is replace it by it's definition, which <code>simp</code> does. In fact, my first attempt was to do that before the <code>ext</code>, which just left me with a goal that the two sets were equal. From experience, the typical way to prove that is with <code>ext</code>, and then I knew (but it would have made sense to try anyway) that <code>simp</code> would make progress on the x \\in ... goals</p>",
        "id": 474095433,
        "sender_full_name": "Ruben Van de Velde",
        "timestamp": 1727805541
    }
